  "prompt": "I am having problems with my friend. She is awesome, but she recently got a boyfriend. I just miss the way we once were. She's all over him and her other best friend. What should I do?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry you're feeling this way. It's tough when changes in a friend's life affect your relationship. Here are a few steps you might consider:\n\n1. **Acknowledge Your Feelings**: It's completely normal to feel upset or neglected when a close friend starts a new relationship. Give yourself permission to feel these emotions without judgment.\n\n2. **Communicate Openly**: When you feel ready, reach out to your friend and express how you're feeling. Use \"I\" statements to convey your feelings without sounding accusatory. For example, \"I miss the time we used to spend together and sometimes feel left out.\"\n\n3. **Understand Her Perspective**: Starting a new relationship can be exciting and time-consuming. She might be navigating how to balance her time between her boyfriend, friends, and other commitments. Try to understand that her feelings and priorities might have shifted, not necessarily because she values the friendship any less.\n\n4. **Find New Ways to Connect**: Suggest activities or set aside specific times to hang out that work for both of you. This can help maintain your bond despite her new relationship.\n\n5. **Expand Your Support Network**: While maintaining your friendship, also invest time in other relationships and activities that bring you joy. This can help reduce feelings of loneliness and provide a broader support system.\n\n6. **Take Care of Yourself**: Engage in activities that make you happy and fulfilled. Whether it's pursuing a hobby, exercising, or spending time with other friends, taking care of your well-being is important.\n\n7. **Be Patient**: Relationships evolve over time. With patience and understanding, you and your friend can find a new balance that respects both her new relationship and your friendship.\n\nIf you find that these feelings persist or become overwhelming, consider seeking support from a counselor or therapist who can provide personalized guidance.\n\nRemember, it's okay to feel this way, and taking proactive steps can help preserve and strengthen your friendship in the long run.",
